Chapter 2 Problem Set

### Definitions
Gradient

an increase or decrease in the magnitude of a property (e.g. temperature, pressure, or concentration) observed in passing from one point or moment to another.

Viscosity

The viscosity of a fluid is defined as follows: Imagine a plane along which fluid is flowing (in the direction) and where the velocity is along the bottom () and increases towards the top (), ie: each successive layer/plate has greater velocity than the one below it.
Successive plates of fluid slide across one another causing friction in a direction opposite to their motion (). For any two plates the top plate will experience friction in the direction opposite to its motion and the bottom plate will experience an equal but opposite force.
eg: if both plates have parallel velocity, then friction will decrease the speed of the top plate while increasing the speed of the bottom plate. Which makes sense because the bottom plate is always slower than the top plate.
For any pair of top and bottom plates with area , the viscous force on the top plate is proportional to and the . Where is defined as the constant of proportionality in the equation .
The term is called the local shear velocity which is the velocity gradient of the plates with respect to their separation ().
If the fluid is such that the velocity varies linearly with , then we can replace with where is the velocity at . In this case, is called the rate of shear deformation, or sheer velocity.

The magnitude of the viscous force is based on . If is large, then there is a lot of friction between plates. As a result, there is less "flow" within the fluid. On the other hand, if is small then the fluid "flows" throughout the base.
